I tried to make a faster form of rebase for the case where the new
base repo state is the same as the old base repo state. I thought that
would be faster because I could just create new trees with `git
commit-tree` which would avoid touching the filesystem or applying
diffs. However, it did not work.

* Getting all the metadata for a commit in one process invocation is
  good. We could do even better by doing git log of the entire
  sequence of commits and get all the metadata for the commits we're
  going to reply in one process.

* However, even if we reduced the metadata acquisition time to zero we
  can't do the rebase in one process. It needs one invocation of git
  commit-tree per replayed commit, and my implementation of that on
  its own is slower than git rebase, so we can't possibly beat git
  rebase using `git commit-tree`.

* git commit-tree is not necessarily itself slow, but it requires that I

  * munge the parameters
  * set up environment
  * spawn the process
  * feed it stdin

  whereas git rebase performs the same logical operations in-memory.

* Theoretically, if git doesn't already have optimizations for when
  it's rebasing onto a base with the same repo state I could do better
  if I used `libgit2`. This is yet to be investigated.

N.B.:

* Could use `git update-ref refs/heads/whatever <hash>` instead of
  `git push .`
